# Lab28: Scheduling Tasks with Crontab
# Goal: Understand crontab basics, list jobs, create/manage cron jobs, automate routine tasks

# ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Task 1: Check current crontab (should be empty for new user)
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────
crontab -l
# Output: no crontab for ubuntu

# ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Task 2: Creating a daily script and scheduling it
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 2.1 Create the script in your home directory
vi ~/daily_script.sh

# Example content you might have added (adjust as needed):
#!/bin/bash
echo "$(date '+%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S') - Daily script executed" >> ~/daily_log.txt
# ... your actual commands here ...

# 2.2 Make the script executable
chmod +x ~/daily_script.sh

# Alternative safe syntax (avoids any tilde/path issues later):
# chmod +x "$HOME/daily_script.sh"

# 2.3 Open crontab editor (nano was chosen)
crontab -e
# When prompted to select editor, you chose 1 → nano

# Inside the editor, you added (or should add) a line like this:
# Run every day at midnight (00:00)
0 0 * * * /bin/bash "$HOME/daily_script.sh" >> "$HOME/daily_cron.log" 2>&1

# Recommended improvements you can use instead of plain ~/ :
# • Use full path:           /home/ubuntu/daily_script.sh
# • Or use $HOME variable:   "$HOME/daily_script.sh"
# • Redirect output & errors so you can debug later

# After saving and exiting nano → crontab: installing new crontab

# ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Task 3: Verify the crontab, then remove/comment out the job
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Check what was installed
crontab -l

# Expected clean output (example):
# Edit this file to introduce tasks to be run by cron.
# ...
# m h  dom mon dow   command
#0 0 * * * /bin/bash "$HOME/daily_script.sh" >> "$HOME/daily_cron.log" 2>&1

# Final check – back to empty or only comments
crontab -l
